name: Kepler-393
scenarioDescription:
The Kepler-393 Exoplanetary System

Kepler-393 is a star with 1.7899999999999991 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.38 times its radius. It is located 2949.36 light years away from the solar system.

Kepler-393 is known to have 2 exoplanets in orbit around it.

Kepler-393 b

Kepler-393 b was discovered by the Kepler observatory using the transit method. Its discovery was announced in 2014-03. Its semi-major axis is 0.09 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. It takes 9.18 Earth days to complete an orbit around its host star, Kepler-393.

The mass of Kepler-393 b is 1.77 times the mass of Earth. The radius of Kepler-393 b is 1.29 that of Earth. At 1.77 Earth masses, Kepler-393 b is a so called Super Earth. Super Earths could be terrestrial worlds like Earth, but they could also be ocean worlds or terrestrial worlds wrapped in a substantial atmosphere, in which case some refer to them as Mini Neptunes. No Super Earths are known to exist in our solar system, but if it exists, the so-called Planet Nine could very well be a super Earth, as it is hypothesized to have a mass between five and ten Earth masses.

Kepler-393 c

Kepler-393 c was discovered by the Kepler observatory using the transit method. Its discovery was announced in 2014-03. Its semi-major axis is 0.12 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. It takes 14.61 Earth days to complete an orbit around its host star, Kepler-393.

The mass of Kepler-393 c is 1.92 times the mass of Earth. The radius of Kepler-393 c is 1.33 that of Earth. At 1.92 Earth masses, Kepler-393 c is a so called Super Earth. Super Earths could be terrestrial worlds like Earth, but they could also be ocean worlds or terrestrial worlds wrapped in a substantial atmosphere, in which case some refer to them as Mini Neptunes. No Super Earths are known to exist in our solar system, but if it exists, the so-called Planet Nine could very well be a super Earth, as it is hypothesized to have a mass between five and ten Earth masses.
